Obesity levels based on dietary habits and physical condition in individuals from Colombia, Peru and Mexico

Regression task estimating the obesity levels based on dietary habits and physical activity

Nicola Rosca

December 7th, 2023

Introduction

Nowadays, the population has access to a wide variety of food with various calories and nutrients. Everyone ranging from small children to elderly people can easily access food that might be detrimental for the health of the individual. With the increase of indoor activities, such as video games and television, the global population has found itself without the proper amount of physical activity. The combination between an unhealthy diet and the lack of physical activity is the reason more and more individuals are struggling with obesity. Therefore, it is necessary to be able to predict someones weight based on their diet and lifestyle, and to be able to offer advice on improvements. The model in this report aimed to do just that.

Palechor and de la Hoz Manotas (2021) have gathered data from Mexico, Peru and Colombia via a web survey. It contains 17 attributes and 2111 records.The attributes related with eating habits are: Frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC), Frequency of consumption of vegetables (FCVC), Number of main meals (NCP), Consumption of food between meals (CAEC), Consumption of water daily (CH20), and Consumption of alcohol (CALC). The columns related with the physical condition are: Calories consumption monitoring (SCC), Physical activity frequency (FAF), Time using technology devices (TUE), Transportation used (MTRANS), other variables obtained were: Gender, Age, Height and Weight. The authors also create the variable NObesity where they categorizes the body weight with values of: Insufficient Weight, Normal Weight, Overweight Level I, Overweight Level II, Obesity Type I, Obesity Type II and Obesity Type III. In this report, I used all the variables mentioned, besides NObeyesdad, because it categorizes the weight and therefore it is not useful to predict it.

The name of the dataset is Estimation of obesity levels based on eating habits and physical condition, found at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/544/estimation+of+obesity+levels+based+on+eating+habits+and+physical+condition.

This report looked at different types of models, linear with and without polynomial terms and k_Nearest Neighbor ( k = 1, 2, 3, 4) that can best predict body weight based on the above variables, using adjusted R2 and MAE as evidence of a successful model. The goal is to predict the weight as close as possible to the real number, looking at the adjusted R squared and the Mean Absolute Error values. Ideally, the best model will be able to predict the weight with no insignificant variables.

Methodology

  • I performed a short EDA analysis on the data set, combined with visualizations in order to see the split of data and possible correlations between variables.

  • The data were split equally into three sets, train, validation and test.

  • I dropped the column titled NObeyesdad, because it categorizes the weight and therefore is not useful to predict it.

  • Some of the variables were categorical, and in order to be able to compute the models mentioned above, I changed the data types into numerical.

  • Firstly, I created a general_lm model that combines all the variables and correlates them with the Weight column, in order to see the adjusted R squared baseline. In this case it is 0.62 without NObeyesdad.

  • I used the backward selection algorithm and the AIC for the initial step of variable selection. I computed linear models without each of the variables that had the highest AIC to see how much they impact the both R squared numbers.

  • I then looked at the p value selection for a more robust result between variables. P values were useful to identify the relationships in the model that were statistically significant and I dropped the variables with the highest p value: NCP, SCPP and SCC. (Frost, 2023)

  • I have applied an ols function from the olsrr library that offers a table with all combinations of variable relationships and I sorted it by the highest adjusted R squared. I used that formula for the rest of the models.

  • The most useful models have been named M1, M2, M3, M4, M5. I ran the predictions on the validation set for each model and I measured the mean absolute error (MAE). The model with the best MAE was renamed Mb and was ran through the test data (new data) to see how it performs. The MAE for the best model was 14.64082, which suggested the model is only 14 unites above or under the real weight.

  • The set seed was set at 16 to be able to reproduce the models later on.

  • The report used RStudio as the IDE, and relied on the tidyverse library, as well as broom, wesanderson, ggpubr, polynom, class, GGally, caret, olsrr, lmtest, and Metrics libraries.

Model Assessment

There are multiple ways to assess model success and how useful it can be in the real world. Most methods look at:

  • the MSE (Mean Squared Error), which measure the magnitude of errors more accurately (Benli, 2023)

  • the RMSE (Root Mean Square Error), which measures the magnitude of errors by squaring them and taking their root square (Benli, 2023)

  • the MAE (Mean Absolute Error), which evaluates the differences between actual values and predicted values (Benli, 2023)

  • the R2 that tells the performance of the model. R2 provides a baseline model to compare with other models, which none of the other metrics provide. R2 is ranges between 0 and 1. (Agrawal, 2023)

  • the adjusted R2 that helps with the disadvantage of R2. According to Agrawal (2023), R2 score is while adding new features in data the R2 score starts increasing or remains constant but it never decreases because It assumes that while adding more data variance of data increases. Therefore, the adjusted R2 offers a more robust model assessment. The interpretation of an adjusted R2 is that the higher it is, the better the model fits and it penalizes the model for using variables that do not improve the prediction.

  • the AIC helps deciding which independent variables need to be dropped in order to find the one that has the highest impact on weight gain and it is used to assess the fit of a model. It is similar to the R-squared, but it has a different statistical basis, according to Pius (2021). The aim is to have a very small AIC because the value of the number itself has no inherent meaning, but it is used to compare different models of the same data.

This regression tasks looked at predicting the body weight with a model based on eating habits and physical activity, and in order to properly assess the model fit, I looked at the MAE (differences between the prediction and the real body weight), the adjusted R2 (to see how high it can go from 0 to 1, with anything close to 0.5 being the best model) and the AIC (that penalizes for use of unnecessary variables).

Linear models

General model

In order to have a set starting point for the report, I will compute a linear model where the dependent variable Weight is twiddled with the rest of the variables. I will look at the correlation between them and try to implement the backward selection algorithm.

general_lm <- lm(Weight ~ ., data = train)
summary_general_lm <- summary(general_lm)

model_summary <- as.data.frame(coefficients(summary_general_lm))

model_summary <- mutate_if(model_summary, is.numeric, round, 3)

View(model_summary)

The above linear model shows a Multiple R-squared of 0.62027, which means some of the independent variables have a direct correlation with the target column and implicitly, with weight gain that leads to obesity. Let us see which of these variables are the most impactful.

ggplot(model_summary, aes(x = rownames(model_summary), y = Estimate)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "purple", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "General Model Coefficients", x = "Variables", y = "Estimate") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

At this point, it is necessary we look at the variables with the biggest impact on weight, and in this case we can see that the Height and family_history_with_overweight are relevant. However, I wondered if Height has a significant importance due to the fact that it auto correlates with the body weight. I noticed that the rest of the variables are concerned just with the diet and the physical activity, and height is the only one that refers to the individuals body. I kept this in mind, whilst I computed the AIC criterion and performed variable selection.

Variable selection

Backward selection algorithm - AIC

The next step was to look at the Akaike Information Criterion or the AIC.

A reminder that general_lm is the model that had the Weight twiddled with all the variables, and that gave us an adjusted R squared of 0.62. I took the general_lm formula, calculated the AIC and then eliminated each variable with the highest AIC one by one to see how it affects the models adjusted R squared.

formula(general_lm)
## Weight ~ Gender + Age + Height + family_history_with_overweight + 
##     FAVC + FCVC + NCP + CAEC + SMOKE + CH2O + SCC + FAF + TUE + 
##     CALC + MTRANS
AIC<-drop1(general_lm)
View(AIC)

Using the generated AIC values, I aimed to compute linear models, extracting the variables with the highest AIC from each model, because I want fewer predictors, a high adjusted R2 and low overall AIC.

I started with Height and highlighted the adjusted R squared at the bottom of every model.

Results of AIC backward selection algorithm

The backward selection algorithm done through the AIC showed that in order to obtain the best predicting model that looks solely at eating habits and physical activity, it is necessary to remove height. Extracting it from the formula, brought the adjusted R squared to 0.4503. The rest of the models had a fairly steady decrease of roughly 5 to 10 units, which shows that their impact on weight is important as a sum, not individually.

I will be using the first model as my M1.

P value variable selection

With the initial set of models computed based on the AIC criterion, I moved on to the p value selection, namely searching for the variables that had the highest p values. As mentioned before, they are useful to identify the relationships in the model that are statistically significant. Even though the backward selection algorithm was useful in understanding that height needs to be taken out in order to have a model that computes only non-body related variables, it is not enough to be able to predict the weight and I believe it can be improved.

Firstly, I looked at the p value of the individual variables, computed in the general_lm model.

Linear models with polynomial terms

The difference between a linear model and a linear models with polynomial terms is that, the latter allows more flexibility to capture non-linear relationships between variables, and linear models cannot always capture the complexity of the relationship. Polynomial terms are useful in understanding the direction in which the data goes, in order to be able to do a better weight prediction. (Agrawal, 2023)

According to Agrawal (2023), the degrees of freedom in a polynomial regression with degree d are equal to the number of coefficients that need to be estimated minus one. It is important to highlight that there are limitations with polynomial terms, such as over fitting the data by using high degrees.

The polynomial terms that I have modified are age, frequency of high caloric food and having vegetables in meals. The reason behind choosing those variables to work with is because in Figures 2, 6 and 11 I noticed a significant correlation between them and body weight.

Conclusion

According to Manna & Jewkes (2014), childhood obesity has always brought adverse and long-lasting consequences for individuals and their families. The obesity issue has increased in the last three decades and the numbers continue to remain high. The authors highlighted that almost 10 percent of infants and toddlers carry excess weight for their length, and slightly more than 20 percent of children between the ages of two and five already are overweight or obese. There are several aspects of a persons life that lead to obesity, not just their height. The dietary and physical activity data used in this report was collected from Colombia, Peru and Mexico, as a result of a web survey and it was collected in order to estimate the obesity levels using decision trees. (Manna & Jewkes, 2014)

This report set out to identify the correlation between multiple variables with weight gain, measuring how each impacts weight through the adjusted R squared measure. The goal was to have a good model with no insignificant variables, that did not use body related data and that predicted weight. Through a multitude of methods, raging from linear models with and without polynomial terms and k-Nearest Neighbor, as well as backward selection algorithm, AIC and P value selection, I identified that the variables with the highest impact on the weight, besides the height, are age, a history of obesity in the family, high frequency of caloric food, consumption of vegetables in meals, snacks in between meals, lack of hydration, lack of physical activity, extended use of technological devices, consumption of alcohol and transportation methods.

The variables were selected using the Akaike Information Criterion (or the AIC), that was run on a general model, where all variables are included in the formula. Based on the AIC, I noticed that height had such a significant impact, that I dropped it in order to tailor the model solely on non-physical attributes. This resulted in understanding that height has one of the highest impact on weight, because it is a body attribute, so I removed it from future formulas.

Using the criterion was a useful start, however no model reached an adjusted R2 of 0.5 or close, therefore I opted to do a p value selection, where I drop the variables with the highest p value, in this case NCP (How many meals do you have daily), SMOKE(Do you smoke), and SCC (Do you monitor the calories you eat daily). Following that, I used the ols function from the olsrr library that generated a table with all combinations of possible relationships between variables, and their respective R2 and adjusted R2. I kept the model formula that had the highest adjust R2. The following polynomial models, M2, M3, M4, M5 highlighted that M4 reached an R squared of 0.4711 and an adjusted R squared of 0.4641, which made it the best model. M4 is the model that computes the weight with gender, age, family history with obesity, consumption of vegetables with meals, high caloric food, hydration, monitoring calories daily, physical activity, use of technological devices and modes of transportation. In M4, the FCVC (consumption of vegetables with meals) brought the R squared close to the desired 0.5 being computed to the power of 9.

After the polynomial models, I run the k-Nearest Neighbor with k = 1, 2, 3, 4, on the training set, measuring the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) to see the performance of each model. None of them brought fantastic result, with the lowest MAE being 156.3213.

I tested all five models against the validation test and measured their MAE, so all models have the same testing method. Out of all five models, only the M4 had the best result of 15.5855. In simpler terms, it means that the model is able to predict the weight 15 units above or under the true value. Ideally, I would have liked to bring the MAE to 5 (indicating that the predictions only 5 units away from the truth), however this is a good result for now. M4 was renamed Mb and was tested against the new data and it gave another result of 15.70838.

Having a model that can predict weight based on diet and physical activity alone is useful especially in a world where child obesity is increasing, yet it is still non-intrusive. The variables considered by the authors of the De-La-Hoz-Correa et al (2019), cover most basis of the diet and physical activity, and I believe they can continue to be used for this purpose. For future work, I aim to tune the M4 model enough that it can bring the MAE to a lower value, ideally under 5.
